# Codex Adversarial Review

Target: branch diff against origin/sentria-qc
Verdict: needs-attention

No ship: the new Telegram status command creates an easy reporter-to-reporter incident enumeration path inside a tenant.

Findings:
- [high] Reporter status lookup bypasses ownership scoping (amplify/functions/incidentFlowHandler/estado/lookup.ts:186-204)
  `fetchIncidentStatus` authorizes the lookup only by `organizationId` and display incident id, then returns the incident summary including reporter name and assigned technician. The Estado handler does not pass caller role or phone into this path, so a reporter can send `Estado INC-0001`, `Estado INC-0002`, etc. and inspect any incident in their organization. This contradicts the existing app policy that reporters see only incidents they reported themselves (`canViewIncident` enforces ownership for reporter role). Impact is user-visible privacy leakage and trivial enumeration of coworker incidents through Telegram. The fix should pass caller role/phone/user id into the Estado lookup and require reporter ownership (`reportedBy.reporterUserId` when available, otherwise normalized `reportedBy.phone`) unless the caller is staff.
  Recommendation: Extend `HandleEstadoArgs`/lookup args with caller identity, fetch the ownership fields needed, and reject reporter lookups where the incident is not owned by that reporter; keep org-wide lookup only for technician/admin staff.

Next steps:
- Add tests covering reporter-owned, reporter-not-owned, and staff lookup behavior for `Estado INC-####`.
